This feature enables your organization to define mandatory and optional skills required to complete work orders. The list of technicians with the most appropriate skills found using Skill Match Rules is used while OptiMax assigns a technician to a work order.

Use this option to view standard SFM Data Validation Rules or to create custom SFM Data Validation Rules. SFM Rules can be designed to show an error or confirmation message when the defined criteria are met. The criteria consist of expressions and optional advanced expression for the target object records.

Use this option to define and manage schedules for automatic, background execution of SFM Transactions on qualifying records. The schedules can be defined for specific days of the week and/or dates of the month. One or more schedules can be defined per day per process.

This feature enables your organization to define the matching criteria between the fields of any two objects and to configure the field map to be applied from the Matched record to the Target record. This is useful when you need to set one or more fields in a qualified Target Object record, to field values from a Matched Object record.
You can use this option to configure push notification for ServiceMax mobile applications.
This group contains various setup and configuration options for Installed Base App and IoT.
Use this option to define and associate Installed Base App configurations such as Layout, Filters, Search, Attachments, and Technical Attributes with the required ServiceMax group-wide profiles.
Set up and manage your Timesheet configuration. Define when the Timesheet Manager runs, what is processed and for which group profiles.
You can use this option to manage questions for checklist.
This group contains various setup and configuration options for Service Performance Metrics.
Module is a collection of related functionality. This screen lists the standard modules installed with ServiceMax and also allows to define custom modules that can be built as ServiceMax extensions.
Use this option to configure the Service Performance Metrics generation criteria and schedule. You can also check the job status of metrics generation.
Use this option to define and associate IoT configurations.
Use SFM App Permissions to show/hide SFM Transactions, SFM Wizards, and SFM Custom Actions on specific ServiceMax applications.
Allows user to generate and purge reports on Technician Utilization and Drive Times based on specific criteria.
This feature allows to define a policy for overnight stay of technicians in an organization.

Ranked Appointment Booking are an advanced form of booking windows. They are defined at the work order, not the case level and are currently utilized by the Optimizer to help negotiate low cost appointments times with your customers. Appointments offered may be either arrival windows, or a promise to complete work within the allotted window.

Use this option to define and manage configurations for Field Inventory on FSA app. Here you can set radius parameter to locate a part, define Inventory configuration for Stock Transfer, choose fields to be displayed in Technician's Stock as well as Catalog, select Product Stock data to be downloaded and much more. Note: This is applicable to Field Service Application clients only
Use this page to turn on/off the execution of triggers that are part of ServiceMax managed package.

Submodule is a specific functionality within a module. This screen lists the standard submodules installed with ServiceMax and also allows to define custom submodules that can be built as ServiceMax extensions.
Use this option to launch the application with which you can import Checklists from an external file into ServiceMax application
Use this button to grant permission to users or profiles to specific features like Checklist Administration

Service Flow Automation provides an interactive wizard-like interface to define Event-Action based configuration. Use this option to create and manage configurations like Push Notifications, Geofence based Local Notifications.
This group contains various options related to Scheduling and Optimization.
Use this option to manage, create and view Output Documents.
Use this option to view standard transactions, define and manage custom SFM transactions. The configured SFM transactions can then be deployed using the wizard.

Use this button to load default ServiceMax configuration for smooth functioning of all modules. This is mainly applicable for configuration only sandbox created for development/ testing purposes. Default configuration is auto loaded on Production and Sandbox instances with package installation. Refer ServiceMax Help for more details.
Settings are configurable parameters based on which functionality in a submodule changes. This page lists the standard settings in a given submodule and also allows to define custom settings.

Display Tags are used in all ServiceMax screens on buttons, labels as well as messages. This screen lists standard display tags installed with ServiceMax and also allows to define custom tags that can be used in ServiceMax extensions.
Setup and manage your FCO Configuration. Define what content is accessible for an FCO, what information is mapped to Work Orders, and which users are notified of FCO processing.

Use this feature to manage the translations of labels and messages configured in SFM Transactions, SFM Wizards, SFM Search,Inventory Processes and Checklist Processes. Using this screen, you can enter translations for the required labels and messages by selecting a language from the list.

Use this option to view standard SFM mappings or to create custom SFM mappings. SFM mappings include field mappings between source and target object records and value mappings for target object records.

A configuration profile contains the settings that control various ServiceMax features. Use this screen to define org-wide profiles with settings that apply to all users, and group-wide profiles that apply to a subset of users.

This feature provides a streamlined way to manage your service organization. Using this link, you can create or edit service teams and manage technicians and their details like their expertise, product specializations and cost.
This link launches an interactive tree-based hierarchical way to manage your service territories along with the scope of coverage and Service Zones associated with each territory.
Use this link to view the standard pre-configured inventory processes in ServiceMax and to create your custom inventory processes.
This screen allows your organization to define rules based on work order information to calculate MTTS (Mean Time To Service). MTTS is used by OptiMax for advanced dispatch optimization.
This feature enables your organization to define how primary territory for work orders are calculated. This is useful when service territories across your organization have varying types of coverage.
This feature lists all the dispatch processes defined in ServiceMax and allows you to create new, edit or delete existing processes.
This feature allows your organization to define rules based on Case information to perform automatic entitlement for cases created.
Using this screen, you can manage the configuration settings for the optimization engine(s) enabled for your organization.

This screen allows your organization to define applicable counters based on Product information. Counters are then used to define coverage in warranty or service contract, capture readings for installed products, and to verify entitlements.

This feature provides the ability to create, modify or delete SLA Terms. For each SLA Terms, users can define the scope of commitment for response, restoration and resolution times, as well as the scope of services included.
This screen allows your organization to define rules based on work order fields. This rule is used by dispatch console to determine the default Subject for new events.
This screen allows your organization to define rules based on work order fields. This rule is used by dispatch console to display relevant information on event hovers in the calendar section.

ServiceMax Offline profile represents a collection of datasets and their attributes, and can be associated with one or more Salesforce profiles. This page enables you to define Offline profiles, data sets and their access permissions.

SFM transaction & docs designer provides an interactive wizard-like interface to define SFM transactions, SFM output documents, rules, and end-user interface. The configured SFM transactions and output docs can then be deployed using SFM wizard.

Service is any activity performed during service delivery such as installation, configuration, troubleshooting, onsite repair etc. Service definition is used in Service contracts to define the coverage for a customer. Use this option to define the list of services provided by your service organization.

Skill record defines the expertise required during service delivery. For example, a networking service provider may list Network Assessment, router setup etc. as various skills. Skills are associated with technicians and used to find the right technician for work order assignment. Use this option to define the list of skills required for your service organization.

Task Template is a reusable collection of predefined task primarily used in preventive maintenance. When a task template is associated with a PM plan, tasks listed in the template are automatically created and assigned to technicians.

Booking window is a named time period of any day. Examples of booking windows are, Peak Hours (10am to 12pm), Late Afternoon (3pm to 5pm), After Hours (7pm to 9pm) etc. Use this option to define various booking windows used by your organization.

You can use this option to configure Service Report feature used in ServiceMax iPad Mobile App up to Spring 13 SP and ServiceMax iPad Enterprise App. Custom fields can be selected for Service Report screen. These settings apply to all your iPad client users.

Using this feature, ServiceMax administrators can assemble various steps such as SFM transactions, inventory processes and other custom actions to enable a wizard-based guided execution of each step. Multiple wizards can be configured for each object
Using this feature, ServiceMax administrators can configure any URL-based action or Apex Web Service that can be launched from a record. Actions configured here can then be used in SFM Wizards.

This feature is applicable for all mobile deployments such as iPad, Laptop, iPhone, etc. Use this feature to define which ServiceMax Group Profiles have access to which View, Standalone Create and Checklist SFM processes.
Use this feature to migrate completed Service Flow definitions from the current instance (org) to any target instance
Using this feature ServiceMax Administrator can configure up to 10 fields that can be edited by Dispatch Console users in the Event popup window.
Options related to general administration of ServiceMax. This includes setting up of custom functionality such as Modules, Submodules etc. and configuring various user profiles.
Options related to setting up various entities in your service organizations such as service teams, territories, technicians, skill sets etc.
This section includes options for managing Installed Product Counters, defining & managing Preventive Maintenance activities, and configuring & scheduling the PM engine.
This group contains various options related to interactive as well as automatic dispatching features of ServiceMax.
Various configuration options available for the mobile and offline deployments of ServiceMax. This includes offline user profiles, data sets as well as options related to iPad mobile client

Options for managing SFM actions, SFM transactions, Smart Output Documents, inventory processes and SFM wizards. SFM transactions can be migrated between two Salesforce instances using the SFM Migrator tool.
Use this option to define how various depots (hubs, warehouses or repair centers) would process their inbound products, and subsequently store/deliver them to their internal locations.
Use this option to define how various depots (hubs, warehouses or repair centers) would process outbound products from picking to shipping.
Use this option to define the sourcing and allocation rules for various types of fulfillment orders (repair or sales orders). Fulfillment processes can then be placed on applicable SFM Wizards.

Use this option to view standard SFM search configurations, or to create custom SFM search configurations. SFM Search configurations include the objects in scope, the fields to be searched upon, pre-filter conditions, and how the results are displayed.

You can use this area to define your service delivery network. Routes & Stops for returned products can be defined as inbound routes terminating in repair/disposition centers. Similarly, you can setup Routes & Stops for outbound parts & repaired products which are shipped to customers.

This screen provides an easy and intuitive way to manage Service Parts Depots (Warehouses) and Stocking Locations within them. You can define multi-level hierarchical structure to represent regional depots, field stocking locations, central warehouses, etc. Within a depot, stocking locations such as receiving, holding, delivery, and staging can be defined.

In this area, you can configure returns process (RMA) for returns originating from customers. A typical customer returns process involves performing entitlement checks and route calculation. One or more RMA's will be created based on destination depots as a result of this process.

Reverse Logistics module allows organizations to seamlessly manage end-to-end repair and logistics operations involving high volumes of data. This includes all operations right from initiating returns through receiving, exchange fulfillment, depot repair to shipping.

Use this option to configure how received products are delivered (distributed) within a depot. The rules should be setup for each Depot, and are driven by a combination of Account and Product attributes.

Forwarding engine automatically creates shipment orders to the next stop in the route based on Route Cards. In this area, you can define which RMA's will be processed by the engine. The configuration should be setup for each Depot exclusively. You can also specify a schedule for the depot.

This area can be used to setup one or more products as alternatives for a given product and establish order of preference. Substitutions defined here are used in Fulfillment Console to drive exchange product fulfillment.

Use this option to configure when Outbound Routes must be calculated from Work Orders and External (reverse) RMAs from suppliers. Use relevant attributes in Work Orders and RMAs that indicate the repair cycle is complete and product is ready to make its return journey to customer.

Use this screen to configure how your end users will use ServiceMax Mobile Client on iPad. You can configure data download criteria, frequency of synchronization, limits that apply to the size of offline data, and more.

Use this option to manage standard and custom Work Order, Account, and Location Views. View definition includes the filter criteria with advanced expression if any, and the fields to be displayed in the result.
Use this option to view standard SFM expressions or to create custom SFM expressions. SFM expressions include the criteria for filtering and advanced expression for the filter criteria.
This feature allows your organization to define rules based on Work Order information to perform automatic entitlement for Work Orders created.

Use this option to configure Proforma Invoice Processes for Service Contracts. You can indicate how Service Contracts are consolidated into an invoice, the type of lines to include, and more. You can also setup the process to run automatically on a schedule.

Use this option to configure Proforma Invoice Processes for services. You can indicate how delivered services against Work Orders and Case are consolidated into an invoice, and more. You can also setup the process to run automatically on a schedule.
Use this option to qualify PM Plans for processing, and configuring rules for creating Work Orders & Cases. You can also setup the process to run automatically on a schedule.

This section provides options for managing entitlement definitions including Warranties, SLA's and Service Plans. It also includes options for configuring entitlements on Case & Work Order, and for setting up invoice generation processes.
Using this feature, ServiceMax administrators can configure up to 10 fields that can be displayed on Dispatch Console map as hover for Work Order, Account and Location.
Activity Master is used to define various labor activities performed by your technicians as a part of service. You can also associate applicable products with these activities.

Use this screen to define PM Plan Templates, which are used for creating Preventive Maintenance Plans. A PM Plan Template definition includes Applicable Products, Schedule Templates, and PM Offerings.
Use this screen to define Service Plans, which are templates for creating service contracts. A Service Plan definition includes coverage information along with detailed pricing terms.
Service Pricebooks contain Activities or Activity Products and their associated prices. The prices are stored as Service Pricebook Entries.

Warranty Template allows organizations to define and standardize their warranty offering and apply it for a range of products automatically. A warranty template can be used to define the type and scope of coverage in a warranty such as parts, labor and expenses, and can then be associated with one or more products. When installed product records are created in ServiceMax, warranty will be calculated automatically based on the pre-defined warranty template associated with the product.

Use this option to manage ServiceMax server cache. The cache contains complete definitions of Salesforce objects and fields used in SFM processes. The cache must be manually refreshed using this screen whenever Salesforce object model is changed impacting SFM processes.

This feature enables your organization to define criteria for finding eligible technicians for work orders. The list of technicians found using Technician Eligibility Rules is used while OptiMax assigns a technician to a work order.
